.SH A) == [[ OVERVIEW ]] == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == #
HFIX wipe clears out created and wasteful files from the programs source code
directory in order to take up less space or force full recompilation.

123456789-123456789-123456789-123456789-123456789-123456789-123456789-123456789-123456

wiping is a two stage process.  first, determining what coult be wiped,
witch is called (w), "wipe", or "wipe recon".  and, second, wiping the files
themselves, which is called (W), "WIPE", or "wipe execution".

WARNING> there is no undo ;)  backup, use git, and pray.  oh, and always
run recon before a full wipe.

.SH B) == [[ REQUIREMENTS ]]== == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == == #
VIDE and HFIX both require gnu/linux and gcc/make (obviously).  additionally, then both use...
   ´ phoenicia, my personal character set (ASCII + 128 special chars)
   ´ zenodotus, my make system and shared Makefile
   ´ vim configuration, at least portions of by .vimrc and syntax files
   ´ yLOG and yURG, as i will not build without logging and tracing
   ´ yUNIT and koios, as i will not create software without unit testing
   ´ yENV, filesystem access library
   ´ yEXEC_uver, for stable forking and waiting
   ´ yCOLOR_solo, terminal color definitions

